Predicting Book Ratings¶

Eric Zhong

Introduction¶

Books are one of the oldest forms of entertainment that have accompanied humans throughout the ages. It is also one of the best ways to throughly transmit ideas, discussions, cultures, and even morality. However, in todays world where attention is one of the greatest commodities, it's harder than ever before to get someone's attention and make them want to read what you wrote. Advancing recommender systems, review aggregator sites, ads, as well as best seller lists are all ways to get attention on a piece of writing. In this tutorial, I'll be looking into how an audiences perception of a book's genre is related to how well it's rated.

The data being used here is downloaded from https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/tanguypledel/science-fiction-books-subgenres. The data is about science fiction books from goodreads.com

Getting the Data¶

We start by importing important libraries as well as loading up the data. We are using pandas since the dataframe structure has some great functionality when it comes to data manipulation, cleaning, analysis, and model training. The data is separated by different subgenre's of science fiction such as aliens, alternate history, etc. We'll add all of those to an array so we can loop over them rather than repeating code for each separate dataframe.

  • year published
  • dictionary holding user votes of what genre they think the book belongs to

Cleaning the Data¶

Let's start cleaning up our data by dropping some unnecessary columns. 'Original Book Title' seems redundant for now and I don't intend to go back and manually scrap from goodreads so we'll drop those.

In [4]:

    dataset[key].drop('url', axis=1, inplace=True)

It turns out that the dictionaries in the 'Genres' are actually strings! Let's fix that by applying the ast.literal_eval function to convert the strings into dictionaries.

In [5]:
for key in dataset:
    dataset[key]['Genres'] = dataset[key]['Genres'].apply(ast.literal_eval)

Next, we'll convert the dictionaries into a dataframe using the pd.Series function and concatenate with our original dataset. This should create a sparse matrix with how many genres there are.

In [6]:
for key in dataset:
    dataset[key] = pd.concat([dataset[key], dataset[key]['Genres'].apply(pd.Series)], axis=1)

Without those pesky words, we can begin normalizing the data.

We'll start by summing up the total number of votes for each genre and divide each genre column so we have a proportion rather than total number of people who voted for each genre.

We can also normalize Rating_votes and Review_number by subtracting the mean and dividing the difference by the standard deviation.

In [11]:
for key in dataset:
    dataset[key]['Total_genre_vote'] = dataset[key].iloc[:,3:].sum(axis=1)
    dataset[key].iloc[:,3:] = dataset[key].iloc[:,3:].div(dataset[key].Total_genre_vote, axis=0)
    dataset[key]['Rating_votes']=(dataset[key]['Rating_votes']-dataset[key]['Rating_votes'].mean())/dataset[key]['Rating_votes'].std()
    dataset[key]['Review_number']=(dataset[key]['Review_number']-dataset[key]['Review_number'].mean())/dataset[key]['Review_number'].std()
    dataset[key].drop('Total_genre_vote', axis=1, inplace=True)

    corr_df = dataset[key].corr()
    adj_df = corr_df.query("abs(`Rating_score`) >= 0.1")
    print(key, adj_df['Rating_score'].shape)
    print(adj_df['Rating_score'])

Looking at the correlations, we see that for a given dataset, a max of 15 genres(excluding the correlation of 1 that Rating_score has with itself) have an absolute correlation greater than 0.1. We'll use this in our later prediction model.

Regression and Classification¶

In this section, we'll first create models using linear regression and decision tree regression to predict scores from audience perception of genre.

Our first linear regression model graphs the actual score vs the predicted score. An 100% correct model should result in a 45 degree line from the lower left corner to the top right corner.

In [14]:
models = {}
for key in dataset:
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(7,7))
    X = dataset[key].drop('Rating_score', axis=1)
    y = dataset[key]['Rating_score']
    models[key] = linear_model.LinearRegression().fit(X, y)
    prediction = models[key].predict(X)
    plt.scatter(y, prediction, color="black")
    ax.set_title(key)
    ax.set_xlabel('actual')
    ax.set_ylabel('predicted')
    ax.legend([models[key].score(X, y)])

The linear regression models do okay but not great. Non of the models manage to get a score above 0.5. Let's look at the decision tree regression model. We'll use what we learned before and set the max depth to 15.

In [15]:
trees = {}

    ax.set_xlabel('actual')
    ax.set_ylabel('predicted')
    ax.legend([trees[key].score(X, y)])

The decision tree regression model performed above my expectations. This may be due to overfitting but I still think it's impressive. With a full depth tree, we may get even better performance although most likely due to overfitting.

Conclusion¶

While we've managed to create a model that accurately predicts ratings from user expected genre categories, it remains to be seen whether the model can generalize. I had planned to cross validate scores across datasets. However, a problem arose where the genre generated from the dictionary for each dataset were of different size. Nevertheless, I have shown that it is possible to create a model that predicts rating with with an error of 1 using a decision tree.

An interesting side note, looking at the correlation between ratings and genres, visual/graphic novels tend to have the greatest positive correlation with ratings.
